# picomatch CVE in Node.js base image's bundled npm (not in our runtime dependencies)
# Affects: node_modules/npm/node_modules/picomatch inside node:22-bookworm-slim
# Safe to ignore: picomatch is only used by npm's internal glob matching, not our application code
CVE-2026-33671

# uuid GHSA-w5hq-g745-h8pq — buffer bounds check missing in v3/v5/v6 generators
# when the optional `buf` parameter is provided.
# Not applicable to this codebase: we import only `validate` (UUID format check)
# and rely on `crypto.randomUUID()` for generation. v14 is ESM-only and breaks
# the ts-jest CommonJS test runner — staying on v11 is the correct trade-off.
GHSA-w5hq-g745-h8pq

# sigstore CVE-2026-48815 — certificateOIDs verification-constraint enforcement,
# fixed in 4.1.1. Same class as the picomatch entry above: sigstore@3.1.0 is
# bundled inside the Node.js base image's npm (npm ≥9 ships it for
# `npm audit signatures` / provenance), NOT an application dependency (0 hits in
# any of our lockfiles). npm is never invoked at container runtime — the service
# runs `node dist/...` — so npm's signature-verification path is unreachable in
# prod. Our own image signing uses the cosign BINARY (sigstore/cosign-installer),
# a separate component. Revisit when the pinned node:22 base digest bundles a
# patched npm (npm bundling sigstore ≥4.1.1).
CVE-2026-48815
